Hi Andrew, congrats again! Below is just some initial information for Monday. I will see you at 9:30am! Let me know if you have any questions in the meantime though. –Julie

Online I9
As part of the employee on boarding process, we ask that you complete an online I9 form.  The I9 is verification that you are authorized to work in the United States.  Below is the information and instructions for the I9 Service Center.
•         Access the I9 Service Center by following the link: https://allegis.i9servicecenter.com/Login.aspx
•         Under the New Employee section on the right, create a username and password.  PLEASE NOTE – Password must contain a capital letter, number and symbol.  Example – Password1!
•         Once you are logged in you will need to complete section one of the I9.  PLEASE DO NOT USE A PO BOX in the Address section. IT MUST be a physical address.
•         Once you have completed section one in its entirety click “continue”.
•         You will need to check the box stating that you are the person in section one and then type your name (it must match the name you entered in section one).
•         An electronic receipt will appear.  You can email or print the electronic signature.  Once you receive the confirmation number you have completed the I9 successfully! (bring this with you to your orientation)
When you come in for orientation please be sure to bring your ID’s with you.  A list of acceptable documents is listed within the I-9 Service Center.

Data Security Training
In accordance with TEKsystems’ Data Security policy and the requirements set forth by the client, you are required to complete an online Data Security training course prior to your start date.  The online training can be accessed through http://allegislearning.skillport.com and by leveraging the attached job aid that will walk you through the process step by step.
In order to successfully complete this training, you must reach a score of 70% or higher, and you must print and submit your certificate of completion to your CSA prior to or on your start date with TEKsystems.  This training will need to be completed every 18 months or otherwise required by the client.  Training will take approximately 40 minutes to complete.  You will use your email address to log into the system and complete the training.
Please note, you will need to have Windows 7 or below in order to successfully access the training.  Currently Safari (through MAC) is not a supported browser to access this training.  If you have Windows 8 or Safari as your browser, you will need to do the training in the Field Office.
Please allow yourself an extra 35 – 45 minutes the day of your orientation to complete this training.

*You can either email me a screen shot your certificate of completion OR bring in a printed copy to your orientation/paperwork time.

Direct Deposit
If you would like to sign up for direct deposit, please bring a valid voided check (printed with routing and account number) with you at the time of orientation if the funds are to go to a checking account.  If the funds are going to a savings account, we need a letter from the bank verifying your routing and account number.   When you finish your project, as a reminder, your last paycheck will be a live check.
Client Compliance
You may be required to complete a drug and/or background check as well as complete any client specific paperwork.  This information, if required, will be sent to you in a separate communication. We will provide approved local locations for you to go to.

It's that time of the year again for the 3rd New Beers Eve Super Beer Tasting Party!  (We've had 4, I think, but I don't remember one of them...)

items.summary: How Not To Fail at Developing and Deploying With Storm
items.description:
Adam Doyle and Kit Menke will lead a discussion on Apache Storm. Topics covered will include:

• Storm 101

• Development

• Testing

• Deployment

• Implementation

Sample code will be provided after the event.

items.description:
Meeting times are 1:30 to 5.  I have padded this invite to provide travel time.

We want to meet you; come let us enjoy your company and exchange ideas.

Implementing a Data-Centric Strategy & Roadmap
Focus on What Really Matters

Presented by:


Peter Aiken, Founding Director, Data Blueprint
Lewis Broome, CEO, Data Blueprint

Data is the lifeblood of just about every organization and functional area today. As businesses struggle to come to grips with the data tsunami, it is even more critical to focus on data as an asset that directly supports business imperatives as other organizational assets do. Organizations across most industries attempt to address data opportunities (e.g. Big Data) and data challenges (e.g. data quality) to enhance business unit performance.  Unfortunately however, the results of these efforts frequently fall far below expectations due to haphazard approaches. Overall, poor organizational data management (OM) capabilities are the root cause of many of these failures. This workshop will cover three lessons as illustrated in examples, which will help you to establish realistic OM plans and expectations, and help demonstrate the value of such actions to both internal and external decision makers.

Takeaways:
•       That organizational thinking must change: Value-added data management practices must be considered and included as a vital part of your business strategy.
•       Walk before you run with data focused initiatives: Understand and implement necessary data management prerequisites as a foundation, then build upon that foundation.
•       That there are no silver bullets: Tools alone are not the answer. Specifying business requirements, business practices and data governance are almost always more important.

Speaker Info

Peter Aiken, Founding Director, Data Blueprint
Peter Aiken, Ph.D., is widely acclaimed as one of the top ten data management authorities worldwide. As a practicing data consultant, author and researcher, he has been actively performing in and studying data management for more than 30 years. Throughout his career, he has held leadership positions and consulted with more than 50 organizations in 20 countries across numerous industries, including defense, banking, healthcare, telecommunications and manufacturing. He is a highly sought-after keynote speaker and author of multiple publications, including his latest book “Monetizing Data Management”. Peter is the Founding Director of Data Blueprint, a data management consulting firm that puts organizations on the right path to leverage data for competitive advantage and operational efficiency. He is also past President of the International Data Management Association (DAMA-I).

Lewis Broome, CEO, Data Blueprint
An innovative and practiced thought-leader in data management, Lewis Broome has more than 20 years of experience successfully designing, managing, implementing and leading global data management and information technology solutions. His successful track record is marked by strong leadership coupled with a passion for driving data and technology solutions from a clear business-value proposition. As an executive in the global financial industry, Lewis led the development of globally integrated data solutions for two of the largest banks in the world. He designed and delivered data solutions (conceptual, logical and physical) and was able to drive standards and deliver timely, cost-effective solutions that were aligned to business objectives. In his current role as CEO, Lewis, in partnership with Peter Aiken has developed a tier-1 consulting organization that effectively combines data management, management consulting and technology into a unique professional services offering.

items.description:
Meeting times are 1:30 to 5.  I have padded this invite to provide travel time and in hopes you will stay for a bit at Mai Lee<http://maileestl.com/>.
Don’t miss:

Karen Lopez
Karen Lopez is a Sr. Project Manager and Architect at InfoAdvisors. She specializes in the practical application of data management principles.  Her speaking style is interactive and engaging. An active blogger, speaker and social networker as @datachick, she hopes to influence attendees to love their data.

She is a chronic volunteer, Advisor to the Data Management Association's International Board, a frequent speaker on diversity in technology, data policy, open data and emerging technologies and a sometimes runner.  She's also known for her enthusiasm for all things space-related.

7 Databases in 70 Minutes (or More)
We’ve been busy keeping relational data consistent, high quality and available.  But over the last few years, new database and datastore technologies have come to the enterprise with different data stories.  Do we need all our data to be consistent everywhere? What does data quality mean for analytics?  Will we need relational database?

Learn how traditional and new database technologies fit in a modern data architecture.  We will talk about the underlying concepts and terminology such as CAP, ACID and BASE and how they form the basis of evaluating each of the categories of databases. Learn about graph, Hadoop, relational, key value, document, columnar, and column family databases and how and when they should be considered. Finally, we will wrap up with 7  tips for working with new hybrid data architectures: tools, techniques and standards.


Bob Schmidt
Data Steward, Wells Fargo

items.description:
About the Presentation: 
Our May meeting will feature Tony Alvarez presenting about how Dataguise can help secure your data.

We are entering into an immersive era of Big Data, where information proliferates freely and accumulates faster than we could have foreseen. Petabytes of data are accumulating and propagating across your business. A good portion of this data comes from external sources and from customer interaction channels such as web sites, call center records, log files, Facebook, and Twitter. This has become a critical problem for Chief Information Security Officers, compliance professionals, and IT staff responsible for data management and security. As data lakes become messier and murkier, what are the best practice approaches that companies can rely on to deliver on the value of Big Data, and at the same time, protect key sensitive information.

Tony will discuss the various options for securing Big Data from access control to encryption, as well as advantages and disadvantage of each methodology.

About the Speaker:
Tony Alvarez has been delivering analytics solutions for more than 20 years across industries and for Fortune 500 companies. He is currently Principal Sales Engineer at Dataguise providing expertise in securing business execution for Big Data driven enterprises. items.summary: DAMA gathering / collaboration with Venture Cafe (Please note times in body of this invite)
items.description:
If you were ever going to do something for yourself, this June 16 is the afternoon.  DAMA is hosted in June by the Venture Café at Cortex Innovation Community, CIC.  All together, here is what you get, absolutely free:
      - At least two great educational sessions (see below).
      - Free beer.
      - Serendipitous collisions with over one hundred community members of the Venture Cafe.
      - Miss Jubilee and the Humdingers.

Tell the loved ones in your life you have to work, tell your boss you need professional education credits, tell your dog to hold it and come on down to the CIC at 4240 Duncan Ave St Louis, MO 63110.  Just go to the Ikea and figure it out from there.

This email is practically endless; surrender now, plan on coming, or read on.

Here is what DAMA folk will be doing:
            3:00 – 4:00    Register with Venture Cafe.  Set time aside for informal conversation and locating the free beer.
            4:00 – 4:45    Chuck Berry Room – How To Make Sense by Bob Schmidt
            4:45 – 5:00    Break and informal conversation, these are the serendipitous collisions we have all heard about.
            5:00 – 6:00    Havana Room - Big Data Strategies: POC to Production by Brett Weninger
            6:00 – 10:00  More Socializing at Venture Cafe while listening to Miss Jubilee and the Humdingers.

About our keynote speaker:
      Brett Weninger, Managing Director, ADURANT Technologies.
      Brett is a business-focused technology leader that has been driving value into organizations for over 20 years. ADURANT Technologies has a 4 year legacy of successfully implementing multi-petabyte Big Data Solutions into production for large clients. Prior to founding ADURANT Technologies, Brett was at Oracle for 10 years where he managed various high-profile internal and client facing programs and projects. Prior to working in Technology, Brett was a Command-in-Control Officer (Captain) in the US Air Force.  While on active duty, he was directly responsible for commanding US and multinational, global air operations in direct support of US Foreign Policy and United Nation’s resolutions.  Brett is a graduate of the United States Air Force Academy.

About the keynote session:
      Big Data Strategies: POC to Production
      This session will provide an overview of how and why you use Big Data, the types of strategies that will make your organization most successful, practical use cases to POC for the Business, Strategic Planning in conjunction with testing out a Proof-of-Concept, and standard risks that are part of any POC to Production Transition. Additionally we’ll go through the differences between Operational Analytics and Deep Analytics, and a practical model for how these efforts support a holistic Data Science Service approach in your organization. These insights are collected from over 4 years of production Big Data implementations for enterprise organizations.

About the other guy:
      Bob Schmidt, Data Steward, Business Systems Consultant at a HUGE bank.
      Author of Data Modeling for Information Professionals (Prentice Hall, 1997).  Inventor of “a method for valuing data” patent:20130151423 A1.
      Bob has labored for decades in an industry that has spawned thousands of millionaires and yet he remains not too big to fail.  His experience spans the life sciences to the mortuary industry.  From the extractive sector to debt collection.  From the Michelin man to the Minute Maid can, he has been everywhere, man.

What the other guy is going to say:
      How to Make Sense
      This presentation is intended for those persons who have intermediate to expert experience with expressing something meaningful or who wish to comprehend or record meaningful expressions should they encounter one.  Those attending may ask, “Isn’t this semantics, ontology, taxonomy…?”  I eschew all these terms because I do not want us to bleed into this talk’s evil book end, “Obfuscation for Fun and Profit.” We will expose the mechanics of constructing meaning as one would explain to Stephen Curry the arc of a falling body; that is you already know how to make sense you just don’t often think about it.  Persons who have a habit of saying, “it’s just a matter of semantics” should consult their ontologist before attending.

Helpful links:
      DAMA<https://www.dama.org/> International
      DAMA St Louis<http://www.dama-stl.org/> … and our MeetUp<http://www.meetup.com/DAMA-STL/events/231178883/>
      VENTURE CAFÉ<http://www.vencafstl.org/>
      CORTEX<http://cortexstl.com/>
      MISS JUBILEE<http://miss-jubilee.com/>
      ADURANT<http://adurant.com/>
      STEPHEN CURRY<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QXiAIxiyVXk> (sorry for the ad)

Why do we do this?  We are fighting a rear-guard action to slow our specie’s slide into isolation and indifference.  Once again friends, into the breach!


Submitted,

Bob Schmidt

Membership Chair-for-life, DAMA St. Louis
Author, Data Modeling for Information Professionals
Data Steward, Capital Markets, Wells Fargo
Titleist
